@baseUrl = https://localhost:60711

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# NER test suite — per-token transformer tagger behind /api/Ner/Analyze
#
# Model facts that shape these tests (see NerController.cs):
#   • Trained on ONLY 5 hardcoded sentences (CoNLL-2003 BIO labels, 9 classes:
#     O, B/I-PER, B/I-ORG, B/I-LOC, B/I-MISC).
#   • Word embeddings are HASH-BASED, not semantic: each word is lowercased and
#     hashed to a deterministic random 50-dim vector. Consequences:
#       - unseen words = random vectors the model has never trained on;
#       - "apple" (fruit) and "Apple" (company) are the SAME vector — the model
#         is case-blind by construction;
#       - "Paris," hashes differently from "Paris" — the space-only tokenizer
#         makes punctuation glue create out-of-vocabulary tokens.
#   • MaxSeqLen = 15: tokens 16+ are hard-coded to "O" without seeing the model.
#   • Entity spans require a B- tag to open; orphan I- tags are dropped silently.
#
# Training vocabulary → label (everything else is out-of-vocabulary):
#   Apple=B-ORG Inc=I-ORG Tesla=B-ORG SpaceX=B-ORG Google=B-ORG
#   Elon=B-PER Musk=I-PER Barack=B-PER Obama=I-PER
#   San=B-LOC Francisco=I-LOC California=B-LOC Paris=B-LOC London=B-LOC
#   YouTube=B-MISC   (note: "European" was labeled O in training, not B-MISC)
#
# Reading the response: bioLabels = per-token argmax tags; entities = decoded
# spans. First request per process also pays one-time training (trainMs ≈ 4 s,
# ~65 epochs to loss ≤ 0.01, 103,433 parameters).
#
# REPRODUCIBILITY: embeddings come from string.GetHashCode(), which .NET
# randomizes PER PROCESS. In-vocabulary results below are stable on every run
# (train + inference share the process). The SPECIFIC tags that out-of-vocabulary
# tokens receive are per-process noise — expect hallucinations of the same
# character on each restart, not the same tags. OOV outcomes below are marked
# "(this run)".
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


### 1. Memorization baseline — the exact 5 training sentences
# The model trains to loss ≤ 0.01 with 100% token accuracy on these, so this is
# the "does the deployed model match its training report" check.
# EXPECTED (verified): every sentence reproduces its training labels exactly —
#   s1: Apple Inc=ORG span, San Francisco=LOC span
#   s2: Elon Musk=PER, Tesla=ORG, SpaceX=ORG, California=LOC
#   s3: Google=ORG, YouTube=MISC
#   s4: Paris=LOC, London=LOC, and "European" stays O (it was trained as O —
#       reproducing the training data's own quirk, not CoNLL convention)
#   s5: Barack Obama=PER, nothing else
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "Apple Inc announced the new iPhone in San Francisco",
    "Elon Musk leads Tesla and SpaceX in California",
    "Google acquired YouTube for over a billion dollars",
    "Paris and London are popular European destinations",
    "Barack Obama served as 44th President"
  ]
}


### 2. CHALLENGE — training vocabulary recombined into novel sentences
# Every word here was seen in training, but in NEW positions and contexts:
# "Tesla acquired SpaceX in London" never occurred; "Barack Obama announced the
# new iPhone in Paris" splices person + product + location across sentences.
# This separates word-identity memorization from genuine contextual tagging.
# EXPECTED (verified): labels follow the WORD, not the context — every entity in
#           all three sentences is tagged exactly as in training (Tesla/SpaceX=
#           ORG, London/Paris=LOC, Barack Obama=PER, Apple Inc=ORG, …). The
#           stack has no positional encoding, so per-token identity dominates.
#           Correct-looking output here is memorization, not understanding.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "Tesla acquired SpaceX in London",
    "Barack Obama announced the new iPhone in Paris",
    "Google and Apple Inc are popular in California"
  ]
}


### 3. CHALLENGE — realistic news sentence, fully out-of-vocabulary entities
# "Microsoft was founded by Bill Gates in Seattle" — perfectly ordinary NER
# input, but Microsoft/founded/Bill/Gates/Seattle were never trained on, so each
# is a random hash vector the model has never seen.
# EXPECTED (verified): arbitrary output — and NOT the safe all-"O" fallback one
#           might hope for. This run produced Microsoft=I-LOC, Bill=B-ORG (so
#           the entity list contains the hallucination [Bill=ORG]) while Gates
#           and Seattle fell to O. Every entity reported here is hash noise, not
#           recognition, and the specific tags change on each server restart.
#           The honest conclusion: a 5-sentence model does not generalize, and
#           it fails by HALLUCINATING rather than by abstaining.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "Microsoft was founded by Bill Gates in Seattle"
  ]
}


### 4. CHALLENGE — case-blindness trap (lowercase common-noun usage)
# "i ate an apple while walking in paris with elon" — a human (and any cased
# NER model) reads "apple" as fruit. But embeddings are lowercased before
# hashing, so apple/paris/elon are the IDENTICAL vectors to Apple/Paris/Elon
# from training.
# EXPECTED (verified): apple → B-ORG, paris → B-LOC, elon → B-PER — confident
#           false positives on common-noun usage, proving the model cannot use
#           casing, a signal real NER systems lean on heavily. All surrounding
#           unseen words (i, ate, an, while, walking, with) came out "O".
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "i ate an apple while walking in paris with elon"
  ]
}


### 5. CHALLENGE — punctuation glue (space-only tokenizer)
# "Visit Paris, London and Tesla." — natural punctuation. The tokenizer splits
# on spaces only, so the tokens are ["Visit","Paris,","London","and","Tesla."]:
# "Paris," and "Tesla." hash differently from the trained "Paris"/"Tesla" and
# are therefore out-of-vocabulary; bare "London" is in-vocabulary.
# EXPECTED (verified): London → B-LOC found; "Paris," → O — one comma cost the
#           model an entity it provably knows. "Tesla." (this run) happened to
#           draw B-ORG from hash noise, so [Tesla.=ORG] was "found" — a lucky
#           hallucination that LOOKS correct but is not recognition (the token is
#           out-of-vocabulary; the tag can differ on the next restart). Beware
#           reading OOV luck as competence.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "Visit Paris, London and Tesla."
  ]
}


### 6. CHALLENGE — MaxSeqLen truncation (entity beyond token 15)
# 18 tokens: "Tesla" sits at position 0 (inside the model window) and
# "San Francisco" at positions 16–17 (OUTSIDE MaxSeqLen=15, hard-coded to "O"
# in DecodeBioLabels without ever reaching the network).
# Tokens: Tesla(0) plans(1) to(2) build(3) a(4) large(5) new(6) battery(7)
#         factory(8) somewhere(9) on(10) the(11) west(12) coast(13) near(14)
#         beautiful(15) San(16) Francisco(17)
# EXPECTED (verified): Tesla → B-ORG reported; San Francisco → silently "O",
#           entity LOST to the truncation window (bioLabels still has 18 entries;
#           the model just never saw the tail). Bonus finding (this run): the
#           OOV filler INSIDE the window also hallucinated — build=B-MISC,
#           large=B-ORG, battery=I-LOC — so the entity list contained
#           [build=MISC] and [large=ORG] alongside the real [Tesla=ORG].
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "Tesla plans to build a large new battery factory somewhere on the west coast near beautiful San Francisco"
  ]
}


### 7. CHALLENGE — orphan I- tags (BIO decoder edge case)
# "Musk and Obama met in Francisco" — Musk, Obama and Francisco were each seen
# in training ONLY as I-tag continuations (I-PER, I-PER, I-LOC) following their
# B- partners (Elon, Barack, San). Here they appear alone at span starts.
# EXPECTED (verified): exactly as feared — bioLabels = Musk/I-PER and/O
#           Obama/I-PER met/O in/O Francisco/I-LOC, and the entities list is
#           COMPLETELY EMPTY. The tagger emits identity-driven orphan I- tags
#           and ExtractEntitySpans drops every one of them rather than repairing
#           the sequence (a real CoNLL decoder would patch I-X starts to B-X).
#           Three known entities visible in bioLabels, zero reported.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "Musk and Obama met in Francisco"
  ]
}


### 8. Realistic mixed newsfeed — 8-sentence batch (memorized + recombined + OOV)
# One inference pass over a realistic feed:
#   s1–s2 exact training sentences (must be perfect)
#   s3–s4 recombined training vocab (should follow word identity)
#   s5–s6 fully out-of-vocabulary news (expect mostly O / noise)
#   s7    lowercase trap, s8 punctuation trap
# EXPECTED (verified): 200 OK; quality strictly stratified by vocab overlap:
#           s1–s4 perfect (all entities correct, including the recombinations);
#           s5–s6 OOV noise (this run: [Amazon=ORG] by luck plus hallucinated
#           [opened=LOC]; Toronto drew an orphan I-LOC and was dropped; Taylor
#           Swift missed entirely; [Wembley=ORG] wrong type);
#           s7 lowercase trap confirmed ([elon=PER], [paris=LOC], plus stray
#           spring=I-PER); s8 punctuation: "Tesla," and "Google," both lost to
#           comma-glue while bare SpaceX=ORG survived, plus hallucinated
#           [all=ORG] [grew=ORG].
#           inferenceMs ≈ 7 ms — barely above a single sentence, confirming all
#           8 sentences run as ONE [8,15,50] tensor through the network.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "Elon Musk leads Tesla and SpaceX in California",
    "Paris and London are popular European destinations",
    "Apple Inc acquired YouTube in London",
    "Barack Obama leads Google in Paris",
    "Amazon opened new offices in Toronto last quarter",
    "Taylor Swift performed at Wembley Stadium on Friday",
    "my friend elon moved to paris last spring",
    "Tesla, SpaceX and Google, all grew this year"
  ]
}


### 9. Validation — empty sentence list
# EXPECTED: 400 Bad Request — "Provide at least one sentence to analyze."
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": []
}


### 10. Validation — whitespace-only sentence buried mid-batch
# Sentence 0 is valid; sentence 1 is only spaces. The whole request must be
# rejected atomically — no partial results.
# EXPECTED: 400 Bad Request naming "Sentence 1"; sentence 0 is NOT analyzed.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "sentences": [
    "Elon Musk leads Tesla and SpaceX in California",
    "   "
  ]
}


### 11. Validation — missing "sentences" property entirely
# EXPECTED: 400 Bad Request from MODEL BINDING, not the controller: an RFC 9110
#           ValidationProblemDetails body with errors["Sentences"] = required
#           (non-nullable record parameter ⇒ [ApiController] rejects before the
#           action runs). Different error shape than tests 9–10.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Ner/Analyze
Content-Type: application/json

{
}
